        {
          "title": "Dictation: Grade 9",
          "subtitle": "How To Approach",
          "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pag2S8wmDF4fbWaAv/recvv23S7ZuwH3q19?XRKkD=recVqTvJ6GPeafHaJ&6J82c=rec29oxFWTUnXF541&home=pago27hsdn3q8TtGK",
          "blocks": [
            {
              "prompt": "Read",
              "text": "Read your books for the week in your various subjects, including Essay Voyage.",
              "imageId": "rec8qCc9QiAta9SiI",
              "image": "../images/howto_images/rec8qCc9QiAta9SiI.webp"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "Narrate",
              "text": "Narrate after you read and copy down any interesting quotes into your commonplace book!",
              "imageId": "recIUhyVu1Y1l6aP9",
              "image": "../images/howto_images/recIUhyVu1Y1l6aP9.webp"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "Practice",
              "text": "You will practice many forms of composition over the year. Your books will often serve as the foundation for your assignments.",
              "imageId": "rec3pksdMr2pnit7e",
              "image": "../images/howto_images/rec3pksdMr2pnit7e.webp"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "Prepare",
              "text": "DICTATION: For one lesson a week, you will prepare to write from dictation a paragraph or more from your readings by visualizing new words and paying close attention to punctuation.",
              "imageId": "rec6mwte9GhEBIan2",
              "image": "../images/howto_images/rec6mwte9GhEBIan2.webp"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "Teacher Note",
              "text": "• As you review your students' composition assignments, be sure to read the instructions in the lesson and give feedback and support accordingly.     \n• Some students naturally integrate and incorporate ideas from grammar and composition lessons into their narrations and composition assignments, but most assignments ask students to focus on one skill or idea. \n• For editing or revision lessons, hold the student accountable to work through the process and instructions given for editing, but refrain from suggesting too many ideas about how they could expand the essay or add another idea. \n• For assignments that ask a student to focus on a particular concept, ignore spelling or grammar edits, and support your student by noticing what they've done well and drawing out ideas on how to dig deeper.",
              "imageId": "recNNZHVLXJY6vLgN",
              "image": "../images/howto_images/recNNZHVLXJY6vLgN.webp"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "lessons",
      "title": "Dictation: Grade 9",
      "linkPageUrl": "https://planning.alveary.org/links.html?id=recmKSiBZiXiTeogS",
      "terms": [
        {
          "termNumber": 1,
          "term": "Term 1",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "lessonId": "recuIpdDppRzUAObA",
              "termNumber": 1,
              "termLabel": "Term 1",
              "weekNumber": 1,
              "weekLabel": "Week 1",
              "sequence": 1,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 1",
              "title": "20m Dictation: Grade 9 - Lesson 1",
              "body": "➜ NOTE\nRotate through different books from your weekly readings to use for dictation.\n\n➜ PREPARE\nStudy 2-3 pages of a passage from the week's reading. There should only be around 5-7 unfamiliar words to you in the passage you are studying. For some books, you might need to study more than 2-3 pages to find that many words you don't know. For other books, you will need to study much less. Maybe even less than a page might contain 6 words that are unfamiliar to you. Adjust the amount accordingly.  \n\nThen, write the words on a whiteboard or a piece of paper. Work to see each word with your eyes shut. You might need to say the letters aloud, write them in the air, and practice writing them until you have the words memorized.  \n\nNotice if the word has familiar parts that can help you remember it. For example, con-junc-tion. Or words with similar patterns that you do know, such as Marian and librarian.\n\nTake about 10-15 minutes. Also, notice the punctuation in the passage. Tell your teacher when you are ready to have a paragraph dictated to you.  \n\n➜ DICTATE\nThe teacher dictates one paragraph, phrase by phrase, from the passage. Afterward, go over what you wrote and correct any mistakes.  \n\nIf you have been doing this for several years, you will have built up a habit of paying attention to words when you read. This will help you remember lots of words and how to spell them. If you are new to dictation, you will begin to notice that you are paying more attention to words when you take 15-20 minutes to practice dictation each week.",
              "teacherNotes": "",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recmKSiBZiXiTeogS&6J82c=recuIpdDppRzUAObA",
              "lessonLinksUrl": "",
              "links": []
